                                 </math> which is used to describe the shifting operation in <math>
                                    <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
                                 </math> whose effect on a vector <math>
                                    <latex>\mathbf{x}</latex>
                                 </math> is to send it to <math>
                                    <latex>\mathbf{t} + \mathbf{x}</latex>
                                 </math>.</para.body>
                           </para>
                        </info>
                     </index.glossary>
                  </para>
               </def.body>
            </def>
            <para>
               <para.body>What happens if we translate an object using one translation vector, and then translate it again using another translation vector? This is called concatenation of translations, and it corresponds to addition of translation vectors, as we will see in the following proposition.</para.body>
